    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-22T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-22T16:00:00-05:00" n="413"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d413">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 659.119/417a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-22T17:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 22, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>339. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> [from
                    War Trade Board]:</p>
                <p>No. 902. On July 20 British and French cabled their respective Governments very
                    fully about Denmark negotiations. That part of cable to Foreign Office stating
                    War Trade Board was prepared to follow the opinion of London and Paris if they
                    agree that the negotiations should be allowed to drop, we have asked them to
                    correct in such a manner as to avoid the Board’s being committed to drop the
                    negotiations even if London and Paris think best. While this might be the course
                    finally decided upon as advisable, we prefer securing the English and French
                    views without commitment to act in accordance therewith until we have had time
                    to consider it. We shall be glad to have your opinion on the whole Danish
                    negotiation after you have read British cable which expresses the Board’s views
                    in all matters except the one referred to above.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PFL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
